content.user_title: Build Graph Neural Networks with PyTorch Geometric
content.value_statement: Graph neural networks require specialized tools and knowledge. This skill provides ready-to-use code templates and comprehensive documentation for building GNNs with PyTorch Geometric. Solve node classification, link prediction, and graph classification tasks efficiently.
actual_capabilities: Generate boilerplate code for GCN, GAT, GraphSAGE models
Load and preprocess 40+ benchmark graph datasets
Benchmark model performance on standard datasets
Handle heterogeneous graphs with multiple node types
limitations: Requires PyTorch and PyTorch Geometric installation
Graph visualization limited to small graphs
Template generation supports common architectures only

best_practices: Always check if your graph is undirected and add self-loops if needed for your model
Use NeighborLoader for large graphs instead of full-batch training
Normalize node features before training for better convergence
Visualize your graph structure before training to understand the data
anti_patterns: Don't use deep GNNs (>3-4 layers) without skip connections or residual connections
Avoid training on full large graphs without neighbor sampling - use mini-batches
Don't ignore edge features if your graph has meaningful edge attributes
Avoid using the same model architecture for all tasks - match architecture to problem type

faq.question: What types of problems can I solve with graph neural networks?
faq.answer: GNNs excel at node classification, link prediction, graph classification, and graph generation tasks on network data

faq.question: How do I handle very large graphs that don't fit in memory?
faq.answer: Use NeighborLoader for sampling subgraphs, or GraphSAINT for sampling-based training on large graphs

faq.question: What's the difference between GCN, GAT, and GraphSAGE?
faq.answer: GCN uses normalized adjacency, GAT uses attention mechanisms, and GraphSAGE samples and aggregates from neighborhoods

faq.question: How do I create a custom dataset?
faq.answer: Inherit from InMemoryDataset for small graphs or Dataset for large graphs, implementing required methods like process() and download()

faq.question: Can I use multiple node types in my graph?
faq.answer: Yes, use HeteroData for graphs with different node and edge types, and heterogeneous GNN layers like HeteroConv

faq.question: How do I visualize my graph and model predictions?
faq.answer: Use the visualize_graph.py script or tools like networkx, matplotlib, and PyG's built-in visualization utilities
